{"timestamp": "2025-12-01 13:30:46.945903", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting diagnosis report — MPLS (BMv2) lab\nSummary\n- End-to-end connectivity between hosts is functional: all host-to-host pings completed with 0% loss.\n  - host_3 -> host_1: 4/4, avg RTT 14.85 ms\n  - host_3 -> host_2: 4/4, avg RTT 2.82 ms\n  - host_1 -> host_2: 4/4, avg RTT 13.73 ms\n- Data-plane (BMv2) logs indicate active MPLS processing (labels being pushed, forwarded, decremented, and popped). No explicit packet-drop or crash messages were observed in the switch logs captured.\n- However, I observed two notable anomalies that point to inconsistent control-plane programming / incomplete table population:\n  1) Missing FEC->label entries on at least one ingress-border switch (packets were forwarded using IPv4 LPM instead of being MPLS-encapsulated).\n  2) bmv2 counter arrays could not be read (the counter query returned empty results for all switches), preventing verification via counters.\n\nEvidence and detailed findings\n\n1) Ping/reachability (summary of tool output)\n- All ping tests returned 0% loss (tx=4, rx=4). RTTs are low and consistent with the topology (host_3 and host_2 are nearby in topology; lower RTT between them is expected).\n- Conclusion: control-plane routing is sufficient for basic IP reachability and ICMP traffic.\n\n2) BMv2 switch logs — MPLS dataplane behavior\n- The BMv2 logs show extensive P4 pipeline activity (parser → ingress tables → egress → deparser). Examples of normal MPLS operations seen in logs:\n  - MyIngress.fec_to_label hits that cause hdr.mpls.setValid() and addition of labels (e.g. \"Action entry: MyIngress.add_mpls_header - 3,\" and subsequent MyIngress.mpls_tbl lookups/hits).\n  - MyIngress.mpls_tbl hits with MyIngress.mpls_forward actions setting egress_spec and decrementing hdr.mpls.ttl.\n  - MyEgress.is_egress_border actions that call hdr.mpls.setInvalid() (popping MPLS) and decrement IPv4 TTL where appropriate.\n  - Multiple transmissions out of egress ports with expected deparsing (packets of size ~98/102 bytes).\n\n3) Anomaly A — Missing FEC→label entries (observed behavioral inconsistency)\n- In several log fragments, an ingress-border decision was made (meta.is_ingress_border = 1), followed by a lookup of MyIngress.fec_to_label that returned a miss for a destination address, and the pipeline then fell back to IPv4 LPM forwarding instead of adding an MPLS label.\n  - Example (excerpt from logs): \n    - \"Applying table 'MyIngress.fec_to_label' ... Looking up key: * hdr.ipv4.dstAddr : 0a070202 ... Table 'MyIngress.fec_to_label': miss\"\n    - Immediately afterwards: \"Applying table 'MyIngress.ipv4_lpm' ... Match key: LPM 0a070202/32 ... Action entry: MyIngress.ipv4_forward - a070202,3,\"\n  - Interpretation: for dst 10.7.2.2 (0a070202) the ingress-border switch did not have a FEC→label mapping installed, so packets were forwarded as IPv4 (no label push). Other log fragments show MyIngress.fec_to_label hits for other destinations and labels being added.\n- Impact: While forwarding still works (IPv4 fallback preserves reachability), the inconsistent FEC->label population indicates partial/uneven label programming across the network. That may be acceptable temporarily, but it means some ingress points are not encapsulating traffic into MPLS as expected. This inconsistency can affect MPLS-specific behaviors (TE, label-based forwarding, measurement, etc.).\n\n4) Anomaly B — Counter arrays not returned\n- The bmv2 counter array queries returned empty \"{}\" (one per switch) in the tool responses. This indicates either:\n  - counters were not configured in the P4 program, or\n  - the BMv2 control API did not expose counter arrays at the time of the query, or\n  - the tool failed to read counters for some other reason.\n- Impact: inability to verify per-table/per-port packet and byte counters reduces observability and makes it harder to confirm any silent drops, retransmissions, or asymmetries via counters.\n\nLocalization (where the anomalies appear)\n- The logs show the FEC→label miss happening on a switch instance that processed a packet with ingress_port = 4 and dst 0a070202 (10.7.2.2). The same set of logs also shows other switches performing FEC→label hits. From logs:\n  - The miss (hdr.ipv4.dstAddr = 0a070202) happened on a switch context that had an ingress_border action for ingress_port 4, and its subsequent ipv4_lpm hit forwarded out port 3.\n  - Multiple other switches show mpls_tbl hits and correct push/pop behavior.\n- Exact mapping of log \"ingress_port\" numbers to switch names (switch_1..switch_7) is not provided by the log fragments; so the most precise localization I can confidently state is:\n  - At least one ingress-border switch (the one that recorded the fec_to_label miss for 10.7.2.2) lacks a FEC→label entry for that destination. Other switches do have FEC→label entries for other destinations.\n  - All BMv2 instances returned no readable counter arrays.\n\nRoot cause assessment (most likely)\n- The pattern (some switches have fec_to_label entries and add MPLS labels, while at least one ingress-border node does not and falls back to IPv4 forwarding) strongly suggests inconsistent control-plane table population — i.e., the FEC→label table was not programmed on all ingress-border switches or was partially programmed.\n  - Possible immediate causes: controller/management-plane failed to push certain FEC→label entries to all switches; or sequence/timing issue during table population resulted in incomplete entries at some switches.\n- The inability to read counter arrays across all switches suggests either the P4 program did not include counters as expected or there is an access/telemetry issue with the BMv2 control API in this environment. This is likely separate but related to management-plane/tooling.\n\nOverall health assessment\n- Functional state: End-to-end IP reachability works; no packet loss on pings. MPLS forwarding is working on mu